content:
At times, you would like to re-iterate a loop without executing the remaining statement within the loop. The continue statement causes the loop to re-iterate and start over from the top most statement inside the loop.Where there is an ability to re-iterate the loop, there is an ability to exit the loop when required. At any given moment, if you'd like to exit a loop and end all further work within the loop, the break ought to be used.The continue and break statements can be used with a label like follows:Code section 3.19: Using a label.


1 String s = "A test string for the switch!\nLine two of test string...";
2 outer: for (int i = 0; i < s.length(); i++) {
3   switch (s.charAt(i)) {
4     case '\n': break outer;
5     case ' ': break;
6     default: System.out.print(s.charAt(i));
7   }
8 }









Output for code listing 3.19

 Ateststringfortheswitch!
